TY  - JOUR
AB  - Because of changes in conditions since the Public Service Commission law was enacted in 1907, the New York Legislature in 1929 created a commission to study causes of dissatisfaction with regulation. The difficulty centered in valuation; and the problem is the establishment of a fixed rate base for the variable "fair value." Division of opinion developed as to the constitutionality of a statute providing for a fixed rate base. An analysis is presented showing why such a statute would probably be sustained by the Supreme Court of the United States.
AU  - Bauer, John
C1  - Full publication date: Sep., 1930
DB  - JSTOR
